Here's the workflow for any new project going forward:

1. Create a folder for your project and copy your file into it:

mkdir ~/Desktop/my-project-name
cp /path/to/your/file.py ~/Desktop/my-project-name/
cd ~/Desktop/my-project-name
2. Initialize git, commit, and push to GitHub in one go:

git init && git add . && git commit -m "Initial commit"
gh repo create my-project-name --public --source=. --push
That's it — two steps every time.

Tips:

Replace my-project-name with whatever you want the repo called on GitHub
If your file name has spaces, wrap the path in quotes: cp "my file.py" ~/Desktop/my-project/
Use --private instead of --public if you don't want the repo to be public
After that, whenever you make changes:

git add .
git commit -m "describe what you changed"
git push